      'result': """CVE-2025-55182 is a critical remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability affecting React Server Components (RSC) and frameworks that implement its "Flight" protocol, most notably Next.js. Disclosed on December 3, 2025, this vulnerability has a maximum CVSS score of 10.0, indicating its severe nature, requiring no authentication or user interaction for exploitation.

The core of the vulnerability lies in an unsafe deserialization flaw within the React Server Components ecosystem. Affected versions of RSC packages fail to adequately validate incoming payloads, allowing attackers to inject malicious structures that the server accepts and deserializes as legitimate data. This process enables an attacker to gain control over server-side execution, often leading to prototype pollution and arbitrary code execution under the NodeJS runtime.

Exploitation of CVE-2025-55182 involves sending a crafted HTTP POST request containing a malicious serialized object to a vulnerable web application. Public exploits became available shortly after disclosure, with exploitation activity observed as early as December 5, 2025, primarily targeting internet-facing Next.js applications and Kubernetes containers.

Organizations are urged to patch urgently, as default configurations of affected applications are immediately at risk. Mitigation strategies include rapid patching, implementing layered security measures such as Web Application Firewalls (WAFs), and leveraging endpoint detection and response solutions like Microsoft Defender for Endpoint for automatic attack disruption. Google Cloud has also rolled out Cloud Armor WAF rules and platform-level protections for serverless services to help defend against exploitation attempts."""
    }
  )
)] role='user'
